# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: australian-rules-football
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:australian-rules-football/16-inch-softball] The first set of rules was published in 1937 by the Amateur Softball Association, in the same manual as the rules for fastpitch softball.
[src:australian-rules-football/16-inch-softball] Game play for 16-inch softball is mostly consistent with standard softball game play.
[src:australian-rules-football/16-inch-softball] In contrast to standard, or 12-inch (30.48 cm) softball, it is played with a ball 16 inches (40.64 cm) in circumference.
[src:australian-rules-football/16-inch-softball] It is common to see higher arched pitching, and balls/strikes are determined by where the ball lands and crosses the batter's body.
[src:australian-rules-football/16-inch-softball] Leagues may form co-ed, all-male, or all-female teams.
[src:australian-rules-football/16-inch-softball] Additionally, teams may choose competitive or recreational leagues.
[src:australian-rules-football/16-inch-softball] There may be rule variations associated with the specific field or league of play.
[src:australian-rules-football/16-inch-softball] When playing in a co-ed league, there may be other rules that relate to the male-to-female ratio of team members and batting order.
[src:australian-rules-football/16-inch-softball] The National Softball Association (NSA) also has a published set of rules governing 16-inch softball play.
[src:australian-rules-football/16-inch-softball] The earliest known softball game of any kind was played at the Farragut Boat Club in Chicago on Thanksgiving Day 1887.
[src:australian-rules-football/16-inch-softball] The first softball was a wrapped up boxing glove and the bat was a broom.
[src:australian-rules-football/16-inch-softball] Play was encouraged by a reporter, George Hancock, who had been looking on.
[src:australian-rules-football/16-inch-softball] Harvard and Yale students played the game while waiting to hear the results of the annual Harvard-Yale football game.
[src:australian-rules-football/16-inch-softball] Until the turn of the 20th century, ball sizes ranged from 12 to 17 inches in circumference.
[src:australian-rules-football/16-inch-softball] The 16-inch softball was eventually adopted in Chicago, perhaps because it did not travel as far as the popular 12- or 14-inch balls.
[src:australian-rules-football/16-inch-softball] This also may have allowed for play on smaller playgrounds or even indoors, accommodating the Chicago landscape and climate.
[src:australian-rules-football/16-inch-softball] Another possible advantage of the 16-inch ball was that it allowed everyone to play barehanded, and gloves were a rare luxury as the Great Depression hit Chicago particularly hard.
[src:australian-rules-football/16-inch-softball] After the first national championship held in 1933 at the Century of Progress World's Fair, the sport grew in popularity.
[src:australian-rules-football/16-inch-softball] A professional league was formed that lasted through the 1950s.
[src:australian-rules-football/16-inch-softball] Teams drew crowds of over 10,000 each night.
[src:australian-rules-football/16-inch-softball] Leagues continue today but not at the same level of popularity.
[src:australian-rules-football/16-inch-softball] There are co-ed recreational leagues, competitive leagues and even a league for Chicago Public School students.
[src:australian-rules-football/16-inch-softball] Many local organizations host regular season play, typically weekly games, as well as their own playoff systems.
[src:australian-rules-football/16-inch-softball] National organizations, such as the NSA, host a variety of tournaments.
[src:australian-rules-football/16-inch-softball] By placing well in NSA tournaments, teams can qualify and compete for the 16-inch softball world series.
[src:australian-rules-football/16-inch-softball] Because local leagues may have slight variations in rules, the NSA world series is played by its own set of world series rules.
[src:australian-rules-football/16-inch-softball] One notable change is that Chicago area players, who typically are not allowed to wear gloves, may choose to wear gloves in world series games.
[src:australian-rules-football/16-inch-softball] Games are played with a deBeer Clincher 16" ball and gloves are used.
[src:australian-rules-football/16-inch-softball] In 1996 Al Maag and Tony Reibel established the 16" Softball Hall of Fame.
[src:australian-rules-football/16-inch-softball] Since inception, the organization has held annual inductee dinners attended by over 600 guests.
[src:australian-rules-football/16-inch-softball] There is a museum in Forest Park, Illinois, a suburb of Chicago.
[src:australian-rules-football/16-inch-softball] 16inchsoftballhof.com The Chicago 16" Softball Hall of Fame is a registered 501(c) not-for-profit organization.
[src:australian-rules-football/16-inch-softball] The game can be seen being played in multiple scenes in the 1986 film *About Last Night*, whose storyline was set in Chicago.
[src:australian-rules-football/1888-british-lions-tour-to-new-zealand-and-australia] The **1888 British Isles tour to New Zealand and Australia** was a tour by a British rugby union team, known at the time as the "English Footballers", throughout New Zealand and Australia.
[src:australian-rules-football/1888-british-lions-tour-to-new-zealand-and-australia] Although a private venture not organised by any official body, this was the first major tour of the Southern Hemisphere undertaken by a European rugby team.
[src:australian-rules-football/1888-british-lions-tour-to-new-zealand-and-australia] It paved the way for future tours by teams which are now known as British and Irish Lions.
[src:australian-rules-football/1888-british-lions-tour-to-new-zealand-and-australia] The team boarded the SS Kaikoura at Gravesend on 9 March 1888, returning to England on the same ship on 11 November.
[src:australian-rules-football/1888-british-lions-tour-to-new-zealand-and-australia] While in Australia and New Zealand the team played a number of state, provincial, and invitation sides, but did not play any international teams.
[src:australian-rules-football/1888-british-lions-tour-to-new-zealand-and-australia] They played 35 rugby matches, winning 27, drawing 6, and losing 2.
[src:australian-rules-football/1888-british-lions-tour-to-new-zealand-and-australia] Only four of the touring party had played, or would play, for their country; Seddon, Andrew Stoddart and Tom Kent for England, and Willie Thomas for Wales.
[src:australian-rules-football/1888-british-lions-tour-to-new-zealand-and-australia] They also played a smaller number of Victorian rules (Australian rules) football matches, but the side had no prior experience of this before arriving in Australia.
[src:australian-rules-football/1888-british-lions-tour-to-new-zealand-and-australia] The team's legacy was honoured in 2013 when the team, along with initial captain Robert Seddon, were inducted into the World Rugby Hall of Fame.
[src:australian-rules-football/1888-british-lions-tour-to-new-zealand-and-australia] The team was led by England's Robert L Seddon and took in 35 games, though no test matches against international opposition.
[src:australian-rules-football/1888-british-lions-tour-to-new-zealand-and-australia] Of the games played the tourists won twenty seven, drew six and lost two matches.
[src:australian-rules-football/1888-british-lions-tour-to-new-zealand-and-australia] The tour was undertaken by Shaw and Shrewsbury as a purely financial exercise with little regard to producing a "British Isles" team, and the team itself is more often recorded as an English team.
[src:australian-rules-football/1888-british-lions-tour-to-new-zealand-and-australia] The two managers were not unfamiliar with touring sides, having organised cricket teams to Australia, and the rugby tour was a follow on from the financially disastrous England Cricket tour of 1887.
[src:australian-rules-football/1888-british-lions-tour-to-new-zealand-and-australia] The rugby tour was not an economic success either and lost both managers money.
[src:australian-rules-football/1888-british-lions-tour-to-new-zealand-and-australia] Worse was to occur when team captain Seddon, drowned on 15 August in an accident while sculling on the Hunter River in West Maitland.
[src:australian-rules-football/1888-british-lions-tour-to-new-zealand-and-australia] The captaincy was then passed to Andrew Stoddart a future England rugby captain and Wisden Cricketer of the Year.
[src:australian-rules-football/1888-british-lions-tour-to-new-zealand-and-australia] A further economic issue that related to the tour was the burgeoning professional movement that was gathering momentum in England at the time.
[src:australian-rules-football/1888-british-lions-tour-to-new-zealand-and-australia] Rugby players and clubs in Britain were divided by the growing belief that players should be paid for their time playing their sport.
[src:australian-rules-football/1888-british-lions-tour-to-new-zealand-and-australia] The growing popularity of the now professional Association Football was causing many, especially in the North of England, to challenge the amateur standing of the union code.
[src:australian-rules-football/1888-british-lions-tour-to-new-zealand-and-australia] One of the catalysts to the split between amateur union code and the future league code, was when Jack P.
[src:australian-rules-football/1888-british-lions-tour-to-new-zealand-and-australia] Clowes, a member of the 1888 tour, was designated a 'professional' sportsman after he accepted £15 to buy equipment shortly before he left for Australia.
[src:australian-rules-football/1888-british-lions-tour-to-new-zealand-and-australia] The other players on the tour were then required to sign an affidavit to state they were not to be paid for playing rugby when in Australia and New Zealand.
[src:australian-rules-football/1888-british-lions-tour-to-new-zealand-and-australia] In addition to playing 35 game of rugby union, the Lions team also played 19 games of Victorian Rules Football (later known as Australian rules football).
[src:australian-rules-football/1888-british-lions-tour-to-new-zealand-and-australia] The Lions won 6 of the matches under the Australian rules, despite having no experience with the code prior to the tour.
[src:australian-rules-football/1888-british-lions-tour-to-new-zealand-and-australia] The uniforms worn by the side on their first tour was a jersey displaying thick red, white and blue hoops, white shorts and dark socks.
[src:australian-rules-football/1888-british-lions-tour-to-new-zealand-and-australia] Two-thirds of the touring party belonged to clubs that, within a few years, would become part of the Northern Rugby Football Union, founding the game of rugby league.
[src:australian-rules-football/1888-british-lions-tour-to-new-zealand-and-australia] Two different scoring systems were in use.
[src:australian-rules-football/1888-british-lions-tour-to-new-zealand-and-australia] For games played in New Zealand and the Australian states of Queensland and South Australia, a try was worth one point, a conversion was worth two points and a drop goal was worth three points.
[src:australian-rules-football/1888-british-lions-tour-to-new-zealand-and-australia] For games played in New South Wales, the points values were; try - two points, conversion - three points, drop goal - four points.
[src:australian-rules-football/1888-british-lions-tour-to-new-zealand-and-australia] The points system for matches in New Zealand was one point for a try.
[src:australian-rules-football/1888-british-lions-tour-to-new-zealand-and-australia] On Monday, 7 May at Lancaster Park, the British played a team of Canterbury footballers in a game under Victorian Rules (Australian Rules Football).
[src:australian-rules-football/1888-british-lions-tour-to-new-zealand-and-australia] The teams were 17-a-side rather than the twenty as was usual at the time.
[src:australian-rules-football/1888-british-lions-tour-to-new-zealand-and-australia] Players in both teams had an incomplete understanding of the rules.
[src:australian-rules-football/1888-british-lions-tour-to-new-zealand-and-australia] The result of the match was a win to the British.
[src:australian-rules-football/1888-british-lions-tour-to-new-zealand-and-australia] The points system for matches in Australia was two points for a try.
[src:australian-rules-football/1888-british-lions-tour-to-new-zealand-and-australia] The tourists returned to Victoria for six further Victorian Rules matches.
[src:australian-rules-football/1888-british-lions-tour-to-new-zealand-and-australia] Prior to their return to Sydney, the tourists played a game under Rugby rules in Melbourne.
[src:australian-rules-football/1888-british-lions-tour-to-new-zealand-and-australia] The locals were members of the Melbourne Rugby Union Football Club.
[src:australian-rules-football/1888-british-lions-tour-to-new-zealand-and-australia] For final preparation and selection they had played a Probables versus Possibles match on the Saturday, 28 July.
[src:australian-rules-football/1897-vfl-season] The **1897 VFL season** was the inaugural season of the Victorian Football League (VFL), the highest-level senior Australian rules football competition in Victoria.
[src:australian-rules-football/1897-vfl-season] The season ran from 8 May to 4 September, comprising a 14-round home-and-away season followed by a three-week finals series featuring the top four clubs.
[src:australian-rules-football/1897-vfl-season] Eight Victorian Football Association (VFA) clubs – Carlton, Collingwood, Essendon, Fitzroy, Geelong, Melbourne, South Melbourne and St Kilda – featured in the inaugural season after seceding from the VFA in 1896.
[src:australian-rules-football/1897-vfl-season] Essendon won the inaugural premiership after winning all three of its finals matches, with Geelong finishing as runners-up with two wins.
[src:australian-rules-football/1897-vfl-season] Geelong won the minor premiership by finishing atop the home-and-away ladder with an 11–3 win–loss record.
[src:australian-rules-football/1897-vfl-season] Geelong's Eddy James and Melbourne's Jack Leith tied for the leading goalkicker medal as the league's leading goalkickers.
[src:australian-rules-football/1897-vfl-season] In 1897, the VFL competition consisted of eight teams of 20 on-the-field players each, with no "reserves" (although any of the 20 players who had left the playing field for any reason could later resume their place on the field at any time during the match).
[src:australian-rules-football/1897-vfl-season] Each team played each other twice in a home-and-away season of 14 rounds.
[src:australian-rules-football/1897-vfl-season] Once the 14-round home-and-away season had finished, the 1897 VFL Premiers were determined according to the conditions dictated by the specific format and conventions of the 1897 Finals System, which was used in this season only.
[src:australian-rules-football/1897-vfl-season] The following table can be sorted from biggest winning margin to biggest losing margin for each round.
[src:australian-rules-football/1897-vfl-season] If two or more matches in a round are decided by the same margin, these margins are sorted by percentage (i.e. the lowest-scoring winning team is ranked highest and the lowest-scoring losing team is ranked lowest).
[src:australian-rules-football/1897-vfl-season] Opponents are listed above the margins and home matches are in bold.
[src:australian-rules-football/1908-melbourne-carnival] The **1908 Melbourne Carnival** was the inaugural Australian National Football Carnival, an Australian football interstate competition, held in Melbourne in August 1908.
[src:australian-rules-football/1908-melbourne-carnival] It was known at the time as the **Jubilee Australasian Football Carnival** because it was designed to commemorate 50 years of Australian football.
[src:australian-rules-football/1908-melbourne-carnival] It was the first time in which all Australian states and New Zealand had competed together in the sport.
[src:australian-rules-football/1908-melbourne-carnival] The winning team was presented with a silk pennant; and each member of the winning team received a gold championship medal.
[src:australian-rules-football/1908-melbourne-carnival] Although the 29 August final between Victoria and Western Australia was played in front of something like 15,000 spectators, it is certain that the crowd would have been considerably larger if it had not also been the first day of the American Fleet's eight-day visit to Melbourne.
[src:australian-rules-football/1908-melbourne-carnival] The official opening was conducted by Sir Thomas Gibson-Carmichael, the Governor of Victoria, at 3:00 pm on Wednesday 19 August 1908, in the interval between the first and second matches of the carnival (the first match started at 1:15 pm, the second at 3:30 pm).
[src:australian-rules-football/1908-melbourne-carnival] The crowd of 7,000+ was in an excited mood: in the first match, New Zealand had come back from a 26-point half-time deficit to win by a single point.
[src:australian-rules-football/1908-melbourne-carnival] The seven participating teams, with each player in their team uniforms, lined up and formed a hollow square.
[src:australian-rules-football/1908-melbourne-carnival] The official party, the Governor of Victoria, accompanied by his private secretary, Victor Albert Nelson Hood (1862–1929), Sir Thomas Bent, Premier of Victoria, H.
[src:australian-rules-football/1908-melbourne-carnival] Harrison, Australian Rules administrative pioneer (then 71 years old), Mr.
[src:australian-rules-football/1908-melbourne-carnival] "Ernie" Wilson, the first secretary of the Collingwood Football Club in the VFL, and secretary of the VFL from 1897-1929, and Mr.
[src:australian-rules-football/1908-melbourne-carnival] Nash, president of the New South Wales Australian Football League, were each introduced to the captain of each team and shook hands.
[src:australian-rules-football/1908-melbourne-carnival] The second match, played immediately after the opening ceremony, was nowhere near as exciting: Tasmania beat Queensland by 140 points.
[src:australian-rules-football/1908-melbourne-carnival] Team photographs of all of the competing teams were published in the Melbourne *Punch*, and the Melbourne *Leader*.
[src:australian-rules-football/1908-melbourne-carnival] Gluyas, Bert Renfrey (Vice-Captain), and Algy Millhouse from the Barrier, and G.
[src:australian-rules-football/1908-melbourne-carnival] McConechy, Ralph Robertson (Captain), T.
[src:australian-rules-football/1908-melbourne-carnival] Watson from Hay, O'Keefe from Narrandera, plus James Greer and W.
[src:australian-rules-football/1908-melbourne-carnival] During the carnival, the New South Wales team trained at the St Kilda Cricket Ground.
[src:australian-rules-football/1908-melbourne-carnival] Paull (Wellington), George Dempster, H.L.
[src:australian-rules-football/1908-melbourne-carnival] Ross (Christchurch), with emergencies, Burns, Welch, and L.A.
[src:australian-rules-football/1908-melbourne-carnival] During the carnival, the New Zealand team trained at the Richmond Cricket Ground and was coached by Richmond's Dick Condon.
[src:australian-rules-football/1908-melbourne-carnival] This was the only time in the history of Australian rules "interstate" football matches that a team from New Zealand participated.
[src:australian-rules-football/1908-melbourne-carnival] It was anticipated that, immediately following the carnival, and before returning to New Zealand, the New Zealand team would play matches in Adelaide, Ballarat, Bendigo, Geelong, Sydney, Brisbane, and Newcastle.
[src:australian-rules-football/1908-melbourne-carnival] The New Zealand team played a match, in Adelaide, on 1 September 1908 (Eight Hours Day), before the Governor, George Le Hunte, on a very wet ground (in several places the water was inches deep).
[src:australian-rules-football/1908-melbourne-carnival] The match was not as one-sided as the final scores indicate: the score at quarter time was South Australia 4.5 (29) to New Zealand 0.1 (1).
[src:australian-rules-football/1908-melbourne-carnival] In the process of the day, the New Zealand team performed two hakas, one before the match commenced, the other before the second half began.
[src:australian-rules-football/1908-melbourne-carnival] Greenwood, and Jack Keir (Locomotives), W.
[src:australian-rules-football/1908-melbourne-carnival] Hopkins (Wynnum), Ralph McKellar (captain), H.
[src:australian-rules-football/1908-melbourne-carnival] "Bas" Bolton was a later addition to the team.
[src:australian-rules-football/1908-melbourne-carnival] During the carnival, the Queensland team was coached by Jack Worrall, and trained at the Carlton Cricket Ground.
[src:australian-rules-football/1908-melbourne-carnival] The selected team was; Charles George Gordon Gwynne, Ernie Johns, Jack Tredrea, Jack Chamberlain, Richard Townsend, Sinclair Dickson, Alfred Roy Le Messurier, Edward M.
[src:australian-rules-football/1908-melbourne-carnival] Hewitt, Stewart Geddes (vice captain), George Wallace, Jack Mack, Tom Leahy, James Tierney, John Albert "Alby" Bahr (captain), Jack Woollard.
[src:australian-rules-football/1908-melbourne-carnival] During the carnival, the South Australian team trained at the East Melbourne Cricket Ground.
[src:australian-rules-football/1908-melbourne-carnival] The captain of Tasmania was Bruce Carter.
[src:australian-rules-football/1908-melbourne-carnival] The squad originally selected was: from the **South**: Roy Bailey (half back), P.
[src:australian-rules-football/1908-melbourne-carnival] Orpwood (back), Walter Burrell (following and back), L.
[src:australian-rules-football/1908-melbourne-carnival] Bridges (wing), Weller Arnold (centre), C.
[src:australian-rules-football/1908-melbourne-carnival] Forster (rover and half-forward); from the **North**: Algy Tynan (full back), A.J.
[src:australian-rules-football/1908-melbourne-carnival] Thomson (back), Charlie Searl (wing), Hastings Woolley (half-back and follower),Joe Littler (forward), Viv Valentine (forward); from **North-West Coast**: B.
[src:australian-rules-football/1908-melbourne-carnival] Mahoney (follower); from **West Coast**: A.
[src:australian-rules-football/1908-melbourne-carnival] Trotter (centre and forward), George McLeod (forward and follower).
[src:australian-rules-football/1908-melbourne-carnival] Appleby (North-West), first back and follower; Norman F Pannam (North West), first forward and second follower; L.
[src:australian-rules-football/1908-melbourne-carnival] Norman (North), rover and third forward; A.
[src:australian-rules-football/1908-melbourne-carnival] Filgate (North-West), full back and wing.
[src:australian-rules-football/1908-melbourne-carnival] During the carnival, the Tasmanian team, coached by Jack Gardiner and Dick Gibson, trained at the South Melbourne Cricket Ground.
[src:australian-rules-football/1908-melbourne-carnival] Before the first match was played, it was noted that six of the possible "Victorian" players, Barclay Bailes, Bert Franks, Bill Goddard (South Melbourne), Harvey Kelly, Paddy Shea, and Phonse Wood had all played their first senior football in Western Australia.
[src:australian-rules-football/1908-melbourne-carnival] "Snob" Polglaise, Charles Tyson, Joe O'Dea.
[src:australian-rules-football/1908-melbourne-carnival] During the carnival, the Western Australian team trained at the Fitzroy Cricket Ground.
[src:australian-rules-football/1908-melbourne-carnival] All of the matches were played at the Melbourne Cricket Ground.
[src:australian-rules-football/1908-melbourne-carnival] Because Tasmania was beaten by South Australia, Victoria was the only remaining undefeated team.
[src:australian-rules-football/1908-melbourne-carnival] Therefore, it was crowned the champions without the need for a Grand Final.
[src:australian-rules-football/1956-melbourne-olympics] The Soviet Union won the most gold and overall medals at these Games.
[src:australian-rules-football/1956-melbourne-olympics] These Games were the first to be staged in the Southern Hemisphere and Oceania, as well as the first to be held outside Europe and North America.
[src:australian-rules-football/1956-melbourne-olympics] Melbourne is the most southerly city ever to host the Olympics.
[src:australian-rules-football/1956-melbourne-olympics] Australia hosted the Games for a second time in 2000 in Sydney, New South Wales, and will host them again in 2032 in Brisbane, Queensland.
[src:australian-rules-football/1956-melbourne-olympics] The Olympic equestrian events could not be held in Melbourne due to Australia's strict quarantine regulations, so they were held in Stockholm five months earlier.
[src:australian-rules-football/1956-melbourne-olympics] This was the second time the Olympics were not held entirely in one country, the first being the 1920 Summer Olympics in Antwerp, Belgium, with some events taking place in Amsterdam, Netherlands.
[src:australian-rules-football/1956-melbourne-olympics] Despite uncertainties and various complications encountered during the preparations, the 1956 Games went ahead in Melbourne as planned and turned out to be a success.
[src:australian-rules-football/1956-melbourne-olympics] Started during the 1956 Games was the "Parade of Athletes" at the closing ceremonies.
[src:australian-rules-football/1956-melbourne-olympics] Nine teams boycotted the Games for various reasons.
[src:australian-rules-football/1956-melbourne-olympics] Four teams (Egypt, Iraq, Cambodia and Lebanon) boycotted in response to the Suez Crisis, in which Egypt was invaded by Israel, France and the United Kingdom.
[src:australian-rules-football/1956-melbourne-olympics] Four teams (the Netherlands, Spain, Liechtenstein and Switzerland) boycotted in response to the Soviet invasion of Hungary, and the People's Republic of China's boycott was in response to a dispute with the Republic of China over the right to represent China.
[src:australian-rules-football/1956-melbourne-olympics] One of the most notable events of the games was a controversial water polo match between the Soviet Union and the defending champions, Hungary.
[src:australian-rules-football/1956-melbourne-olympics] The Soviet Union had recently suppressed an anti-authoritarian revolution in Hungary and violence broke out between the teams during the match, resulting in numerous injuries.
[src:australian-rules-football/1956-melbourne-olympics] When Hungary's Ervin Zádor suffered bleeding after being punched by the Soviet Union's Valentin Prokopov, spectators attempted to join the violence, but they were blocked by police.
[src:australian-rules-football/1956-melbourne-olympics] The match was cancelled, with Hungary being declared the winner because they were in the lead 4–0.
[src:australian-rules-football/1956-melbourne-olympics] Melbourne was selected as the host city over bids from Buenos Aires, Mexico City, Montreal, Los Angeles, Detroit, Chicago, Minneapolis, Philadelphia, and San Francisco at the 43rd IOC Session in Rome, Italy on 28 April 1949.
[src:australian-rules-football/1956-melbourne-olympics] Mexico City, Montreal and Los Angeles would eventually be selected to host the 1968, 1976 and 1984 Summer Olympics respectively.
[src:australian-rules-football/1956-melbourne-olympics] Many members of the IOC were skeptical about Melbourne as an appropriate site.
[src:australian-rules-football/1956-melbourne-olympics] Its location in the Southern Hemisphere was a major concern since the reversal of seasons would mean the Games must be held during the northern winter.
[src:australian-rules-football/1956-melbourne-olympics] The November–December schedule was thought likely to inconvenience athletes from the Northern Hemisphere, who were accustomed to resting during their winter.
[src:australian-rules-football/1956-melbourne-olympics] Notwithstanding these concerns, the field of candidates eventually narrowed to two Southern Hemisphere cities, these being Melbourne and Buenos Aires, Argentina.
[src:australian-rules-football/1956-melbourne-olympics] Melbourne was selected, in 1949, to host the 1956 Olympics by a one-vote margin.
[src:australian-rules-football/1956-melbourne-olympics] The first sign of trouble was the revelation that Australian equine quarantine would prevent the country from hosting the equestrian events.
[src:australian-rules-football/1956-melbourne-olympics] Stockholm was selected as the alternative site, so equestrian competition began on 10 June, five and a half months before the rest of the Olympic Games were to open.
[src:australian-rules-football/1956-melbourne-olympics] The above problems of the Melbourne Games were compounded by bickering over financing among Australian politicians.
[src:australian-rules-football/1956-melbourne-olympics] Eventually, in March 1953, the State Government accepted a £2 million loan from the Commonwealth Government to build the Olympic Village, which would accommodate up to 6,000 people, in Heidelberg West.
[src:australian-rules-football/1956-melbourne-olympics] After the Olympics, the houses in the village were handed back to the Housing Commission for general public housing.
[src:australian-rules-football/1956-melbourne-olympics] At one point, IOC President Avery Brundage suggested that Rome, which was to host the 1960 Games, was so far ahead of Melbourne in preparations that it might be ready as a replacement site in 1956.
[src:australian-rules-football/1956-melbourne-olympics] Constructing of the sporting venues was given priority over the athlete's village.
[src:australian-rules-football/1956-melbourne-olympics] The village was designed as a whole new suburb with semi-detached houses and flats, the first village that both sexes could cohabitate the same buildings instead of gender designated sections.
[src:australian-rules-football/1956-melbourne-olympics] As late as April 1955, Brundage, who was presiding over the Olympics for the first time, was still doubtful about Melbourne and was not satisfied by an inspection trip to the city.
[src:australian-rules-football/1956-melbourne-olympics] Construction was well under way by then, thanks to a $4.5 million federal loan to Victoria, but it was behind schedule.
[src:australian-rules-football/1956-melbourne-olympics] He still held out the possibility that Rome might have to step in.
[src:australian-rules-football/1956-melbourne-olympics] By the beginning of 1956, though, it was obvious that Melbourne would be ready for the Olympics.
[src:australian-rules-football/1956-melbourne-olympics] Egypt, Iraq, Cambodia and Lebanon announced that they would not participate in the Olympics in response to the Suez Crisis when Egypt was invaded by Israel, the United Kingdom, and France.
[src:australian-rules-football/1956-melbourne-olympics] The Netherlands, Spain, Switzerland and Liechtenstein boycotted the event in protest of the Soviet Union's crushing of the Hungarian Revolution.
[src:australian-rules-football/1956-melbourne-olympics] The People's Republic of China chose to boycott the event because Taiwan had been allowed to compete.
[src:australian-rules-football/1956-melbourne-olympics] Athletes from both East and West Germany competed together as a combined team (a display of unity that was repeated in 1960 and 1964, but was then discontinued).
[src:australian-rules-football/1956-melbourne-olympics] Although the number of countries participating (67) was almost the same as in 1952 (69), the number of athletes competing dropped sharply, from 4,925 to 3,342.
[src:australian-rules-football/1956-melbourne-olympics] Once underway, the Games progressed smoothly, and came to be known as the "Friendly Games".
[src:australian-rules-football/1956-melbourne-olympics] Betty Cuthbert, an 18-year-old from Sydney, won the 100 and 200 metre sprint races and ran an exceptional final leg in the 4 x 100 metre relay to overcome Great Britain's lead and claim her third gold medal, becoming known as the "Golden Girl".
[src:australian-rules-football/1956-melbourne-olympics] The veteran Shirley Strickland repeated her 1952 win in the 80 metre hurdles and was also part of the winning 4 x 100 metre relay team, bringing her career Olympic medal total to seven: three golds, a silver, and three bronze medals.
[src:australian-rules-football/1956-melbourne-olympics] They won all of the freestyle races, men's and women's, and collected a total of eight gold, four silver and two bronze medals.
[src:australian-rules-football/1956-melbourne-olympics] Murray Rose became the first male swimmer to win two freestyle events (and a total three events) since Johnny Weissmuller in 1924, while Dawn Fraser won gold medals in the 100 metre freestyle and as the leadoff swimmer in the 4 x 100 metre relay team.
[src:australian-rules-football/1956-melbourne-olympics] The men's track and field events were dominated by the United States.
[src:australian-rules-football/1956-melbourne-olympics] They not only won 15 of the 24 events, they swept four of them and took first and second place in five others.
[src:australian-rules-football/1956-melbourne-olympics] Bobby Morrow led the way with gold medals in the 100 and 200 metre sprints and the 4 x 100 metre relay.
[src:australian-rules-football/1956-melbourne-olympics] Tom Courtney barely overtook Great Britain's Derek Johnson in the 800 metre run, then collapsed from the exertion and needed medical attention.
[src:australian-rules-football/1956-melbourne-olympics] Ireland's Ronnie Delany ran an outstanding 53.8 over the last 400 metres to win the 1,500 metre run (also Ireland's last gold medal in track events), in which favourite John Landy of Australia finished third.
[src:australian-rules-football/1956-melbourne-olympics] There was a major upset, marred briefly by controversy, in the 3,000 metre steeplechase.
[src:australian-rules-football/1956-melbourne-olympics] Little-known Chris Brasher of Great Britain finished well ahead of the field, but the judges disqualified him for interfering with Norway's Ernst Larsen, and they announced Sándor Rozsnyói of Hungary as the winner.
[src:australian-rules-football/1956-melbourne-olympics] Brasher's appeal was supported by Larsen, Rozsnyói, and fourth-place finisher Heinz Laufer of Germany.
[src:australian-rules-football/1956-melbourne-olympics] Subsequently, the decision was reversed and Brasher became the first Briton to win a gold medal in track and field since 1936.
[src:australian-rules-football/1956-melbourne-olympics] Soviet runner Vladimir Kuts won two golds by winning both the 5,000-metre and 10,000-metre events.
[src:australian-rules-football/1956-melbourne-olympics] Only two world records were set in track and field.
[src:australian-rules-football/1956-melbourne-olympics] Mildred McDaniel, the first American woman to win gold in the sport, set a high jump record of 1.76 metres (5.8 ft), and Egil Danielsen of Norway overcame blustery conditions with a remarkable javelin throw of 85.71 metres (281.2 ft).
[src:australian-rules-football/1956-melbourne-olympics] Throughout the Olympics, Hungarian athletes were cheered by fans from Australia and other countries.
[src:australian-rules-football/1956-melbourne-olympics] Many of them gathered in the boxing arena when thirty-year-old Laszlo Papp of Hungary won a record third gold medal by beating José Torres for the light-middleweight championship.
[src:australian-rules-football/1956-melbourne-olympics] A few days later, the crowd was with the Hungarian water polo team in its hotly contested and emotionally charged match against the Soviet Union which took place against the background of the Soviet invasion of Hungary.
[src:australian-rules-football/1956-melbourne-olympics] The game became rough and, when a Hungarian was forced to leave the pool with a bleeding wound above his eye, a riot almost broke out.
[src:australian-rules-football/1956-melbourne-olympics] The police restored order and the game was called early, with Hungary leading 4–0, and the Hungarians went on to win the gold medal.
[src:australian-rules-football/1956-melbourne-olympics] In a much publicized Olympic romance, American hammer throw champion Hal Connolly would marry Czechoslovak discus throw champion, Olga Fikotová.
[src:australian-rules-football/1956-melbourne-olympics] After moving to the United States, Olga wanted to continue representing Czechoslovakia, but the Czechoslovak Olympic Committee would not allow her to do so.
[src:australian-rules-football/1956-melbourne-olympics] Thereafter, as Olga Connolly, she took part in every Olympics until 1972 competing for the U.S.
[src:australian-rules-football/1956-melbourne-olympics] She was the flag bearer for the U.S. team at the 1972 Summer Olympics.
[src:australian-rules-football/1956-melbourne-olympics] The India men's national field hockey team won its sixth consecutive Olympic gold.
[src:australian-rules-football/1956-melbourne-olympics] Despite the international tensions of 1956—or perhaps because of them—a young Melburnian, John Ian Wing, came up with a new idea for the closing ceremony.
[src:australian-rules-football/1956-melbourne-olympics] Instead of marching as separate teams, behind their national flags, the athletes mingled together as they paraded into and around the arena for a final appearance before the spectators.
[src:australian-rules-football/1956-melbourne-olympics] It was the start of an Olympic tradition that has been followed ever since.
[src:australian-rules-football/1956-melbourne-olympics] The Olympic flame was relayed to Melbourne after being lit at Olympia on 2 November 1956.
[src:australian-rules-football/1956-melbourne-olympics] Greek runners took the flame from Olympia to Athens.
[src:australian-rules-football/1956-melbourne-olympics] The flame was then transferred to a miner's lamp, flown by a Qantas Super Constellation aircraft, "Southern Horizon" to Darwin, Northern Territory.
[src:australian-rules-football/1956-melbourne-olympics] A Royal Australian Air Force English Electric Canberra jet bomber transported the flame to Cairns, Queensland, where it arrived on 9 November 1956 and the Mayor of Cairns, Alderman W.J.
[src:australian-rules-football/1956-melbourne-olympics] Fulton, lit the first torch with the torch design was identical to the one used for the 1948 London Games (except for the engraved city name and year).
[src:australian-rules-football/1956-melbourne-olympics] The first runner was Con Verevis, a local man of Greek parentage.
[src:australian-rules-football/1956-melbourne-olympics] The flame was relayed down the east coast of Australia using die cast aluminium torches weighing about 3 pounds (1.8 kg).
[src:australian-rules-football/1956-melbourne-olympics] The flame arrived in Melbourne on 22 November 1956, the day of the opening ceremony and The flame was lit at the Olympic stadium by Ron Clarke, who accidentally burned his arm in the process.
[src:australian-rules-football/1956-melbourne-olympics] While the Olympic flame was being carried to Sydney, an Australian veterinary student named Barry Larkin carried a fake Olympic Flame and fooled the mayor of Sydney.
[src:australian-rules-football/1956-melbourne-olympics] The Melbourne Olympic Arts Festival was an arts festival held in conjunction with the Olympics.
[src:australian-rules-football/1956-melbourne-olympics] The Olympics were first televised during the 1936 games to a domestic audience in Berlin.
[src:australian-rules-football/1956-melbourne-olympics] The 1956 Winter Olympics in Cortina d'Ampezzo were broadcast internationally with the organising committee giving the television rights gratis.
[src:australian-rules-football/1956-melbourne-olympics] While there was much interest in the games overseas, no international television or newsreel rights were awarded, as the Melbourne organising committee requested licensing payments for the broadcasting rights.
[src:australian-rules-football/1956-melbourne-olympics] However, domestic rights to the games were hastily agreed by the then three Melbourne stations, GTV9, HSV7 and ABV2, only a week before the opening ceremony.
[src:australian-rules-football/1956-melbourne-olympics] The three Sydney stations, TCN9, ATN7 and ABN2, syndicated the Melbourne coverage.
[src:australian-rules-football/1956-melbourne-olympics] Television in Australia was new, having its beginnings in September 1956.
[src:australian-rules-football/1956-melbourne-olympics] For many Australians, their first glimpse of television were Olympic broadcasts.
[src:australian-rules-football/1956-melbourne-olympics] Around five thousand television sets were in Australia by the time of the Games, so the domestic audience largely watched the games at community halls and at Ampol petrol stations.
[src:australian-rules-football/1956-melbourne-olympics] The 1956 Summer Olympics featured 17 different sports encompassing 23 disciplines, and medals were awarded in 151 events (145 events in Melbourne and 6 equestrian events in Stockholm).
[src:australian-rules-football/1956-melbourne-olympics] In the list below, the number of events in each discipline is noted in parentheses.
[src:australian-rules-football/1956-melbourne-olympics] A total of 67 nations competed in the 1956 Olympics.
[src:australian-rules-football/1956-melbourne-olympics] Eight countries made their Olympic debuts: Cambodia (only competed in the equestrian events in Stockholm), Ethiopia, Fiji, Kenya, Liberia, Malaya, North Borneo (modern-day Sabah of Malaysia), and Uganda.
[src:australian-rules-football/1956-melbourne-olympics] Athletes from East Germany and West Germany competed together as the United Team of Germany, an arrangement that would last until 1968.
[src:australian-rules-football/1956-melbourne-olympics] For the first time, the team of Republic of China effectively represented only Taiwan.
[src:australian-rules-football/1956-melbourne-olympics] Five nations competed in the equestrian events in Stockholm, but did not attend the Games in Melbourne.
[src:australian-rules-football/1956-melbourne-olympics] Cambodia, Egypt and Lebanon did not compete in Melbourne due to a boycott regarding the Suez Crisis, whilst the Netherlands, Spain and Switzerland all boycotted the Melbourne Olympics in protest at the Soviet invasion of Hungary.
[src:australian-rules-football/1956-melbourne-olympics] Nations that returned to the games in this edition included Afghanistan and Colombia.
[src:australian-rules-football/1956-melbourne-olympics] Nations that participated in the previous games in Helsinki 1952 but was absent in Melbourne 1956 included the People's Republic of China, Liechtenstein, Netherlands Antilles, and Saar.
[src:australian-rules-football/1956-melbourne-olympics] Puerto Rico is an unincorporated territory and commonwealth of the United States.
[src:australian-rules-football/1956-melbourne-olympics] Bahamas, Bermuda, Fiji, Gold Coast (modern-day Ghana), Hong Kong, Jamaica, Kenya, Nigeria, Malaya, North Borneo, Singapore, Trinidad and Tobago, Uganda and British Guyana was all part of the British Empire.
[src:australian-rules-football/1956-melbourne-olympics] These are the top ten nations that won medals at the 1956 Games.
[src:australian-rules-football/1982-commonwealth-games] The **1982 Commonwealth Games** were held in Brisbane, Australia, from 30 September to 9 October 1982.
[src:australian-rules-football/1982-commonwealth-games] The Opening Ceremony was held at the QEII Stadium (named after Elizabeth II), in the Brisbane suburb of Nathan.
[src:australian-rules-football/1982-commonwealth-games] The QEII Stadium was also the athletics and archery events venue.
[src:australian-rules-football/1982-commonwealth-games] Other events were held at the purpose-built Sleeman Sports Complex in Chandler.
[src:australian-rules-football/1982-commonwealth-games] The Chairman of the 1982 Commonwealth Games was Sir Edward Williams.
[src:australian-rules-football/1982-commonwealth-games] The 1982 Commonwealth Games Logo was designed by Hugh Edwards.
[src:australian-rules-football/1982-commonwealth-games] The symbol is derived from the form of a bounding kangaroo.
[src:australian-rules-football/1982-commonwealth-games] The three bands, forming stylized A's (for Australia), and is in colours which are common to flags of many Commonwealth countries.
[src:australian-rules-football/1982-commonwealth-games] The mascot for the games was also designed by Hugh Edwards and is a caricature of a kangaroo was named Matilda.
[src:australian-rules-football/1982-commonwealth-games] A 13-meter-high (43-foot) mechanical kangaroo travelled around the stadium and winked at the crowd.
[src:australian-rules-football/1982-commonwealth-games] The event was officially opened by The Duke of Edinburgh and closed by Elizabeth II.
[src:australian-rules-football/1982-commonwealth-games] Bidding for the XII Commonwealth Games was held in Montreal, Canada, at the 1976 Montreal Summer Olympics.
[src:australian-rules-football/1982-commonwealth-games] Lagos, Brisbane, Kuala Lumpur, and Birmingham were the bidding cities.
[src:australian-rules-football/1982-commonwealth-games] On 14 July 1976, it was announced that Brisbane had won the rights to stage the Games after the other candidate cities withdrew bids.
[src:australian-rules-football/1982-commonwealth-games] Sixteen years after the Brisbane Games, Kuala Lumpur hosted the 1998 Commonwealth Games, while Birmingham hosted the 2022 Commonwealth Games.
[src:australian-rules-football/1982-commonwealth-games] Brisbane was awarded the Games by default after being the only candidate city left at the bid election after Birmingham reversed its decision to submit an application.
[src:australian-rules-football/1982-commonwealth-games] Nigeria's boycott of the 1976 Summer Olympics in Montreal made Lagos' bid lobbying impractical.
[src:australian-rules-football/1982-commonwealth-games] The 1976 Summer Olympics in Montreal were plagued with cost overruns, and bidding on a sports festival anywhere in the world was not good politically.
[src:australian-rules-football/1982-commonwealth-games] Forty-six Commonwealth nations and territories took part in the 1982 Commonwealth Games.
[src:australian-rules-football/1982-commonwealth-games] A total of 1,583 athletes and 571 officials participated in the event.
[src:australian-rules-football/1982-commonwealth-games] The Griffith University student dormitories in the adjoining Nathan Campus were used as athletes' villages.
[src:australian-rules-football/1982-commonwealth-games] The ceremony at the QEII Stadium was held on a fine but extremely windy day.
[src:australian-rules-football/1982-commonwealth-games] The wind was so strong that skydivers who were going to descend into the stadium were cancelled.
[src:australian-rules-football/1982-commonwealth-games] Instead they made an entrance at the closing ceremony.
[src:australian-rules-football/1982-commonwealth-games] Elizabeth II closed the Games during a colourful ceremony, which included parachute jumpers (who had originally been also intended as part of the Opening Ceremony display) jumping and landing in a special target area within the stadium and red, white and blue balloons.
[src:australian-rules-football/1982-commonwealth-games] Matilda the Kangaroo also winked at the Queen.
[src:australian-rules-football/1982-commonwealth-games] Following the closing of the Games, the Queen and the Duke left the stand to be driven from the stadium.
[src:australian-rules-football/1982-commonwealth-games] However, nobody wanted the Games to end and the Australian team formed a 'guard of honour' and ran beside and behind the car in which Queen Elizabeth and Prince Philip were travelling, as it circled the stadium several times before finally leaving.
[src:australian-rules-football/1982-commonwealth-games] Team members from other countries also joined in running after the royal car.
[src:australian-rules-football/1982-commonwealth-games] Sports contested during the 1982 Commonwealth Games included athletics, archery, badminton, lawn bowls, boxing, cycling, shooting, swimming, diving, weightlifting and wrestling.
[src:australian-rules-football/1982-commonwealth-games] Table tennis and Australian rules football were demonstration sports, with the latter being demonstrated at a 6 October rematch at the Gabba of that year's VFL Grand Final, which took place just 11 days before at the Melbourne Cricket Ground.
[src:australian-rules-football/1982-commonwealth-games] Richmond won the demonstration rematch with a score of 28.16 (184) to Carlton's 26.10 (166).
[src:australian-rules-football/1982-commonwealth-games] This is the full table of the **medal count** of the **1982 Commonwealth Games**.
[src:australian-rules-football/1982-commonwealth-games] These rankings sort by the number of gold medals earned by a country.
[src:australian-rules-football/1982-commonwealth-games] The number of silvers is taken into consideration next and then the number of bronze.
[src:australian-rules-football/1982-commonwealth-games] If, after the above, countries are still tied, equal ranking is given and they are listed alphabetically.
[src:australian-rules-football/1982-commonwealth-games] This follows the system used by the IOC, IAAF and BBC.
[src:australian-rules-football/1982-commonwealth-games] The first event of the Games was 100 kilometres (62 mi) Road Trial in cycling.
[src:australian-rules-football/1982-commonwealth-games] England won the Gold Medal in the event, and Australia won the Silver Medal—coming second to England by only six seconds.
[src:australian-rules-football/1982-commonwealth-games] Other sports which were contested on the first day of competition included swimming and diving, weightlifting, shooting and bowls.
[src:australian-rules-football/1982-commonwealth-games] Sports contested included swimming, diving, weightlifting, shooting, cycling, bowls and archery.
[src:australian-rules-football/1982-commonwealth-games] The day was marred by both Australia and Canada being disqualified in the 4 × 100 metres relay in swimming, both problems occurring during change-overs.
[src:australian-rules-football/1982-commonwealth-games] The medals awarded for this race went to England, Scotland and New Zealand.
[src:australian-rules-football/1982-commonwealth-games] Sports contested included swimming, diving, cycling, athletics, archery, hammer throwing and shooting.
[src:australian-rules-football/1982-commonwealth-games] The day was marred when Canada was again disqualified, this time in the 4 × 200 metres freestyle relay.
[src:australian-rules-football/1982-commonwealth-games] Canada protested against the winners, Australia, as well as against their own disqualification.
[src:australian-rules-football/1982-commonwealth-games] One of the targets of the protests was Queensland's *Aborigines Act 1971*, which restricted and controlled the lives of Aboriginal people in Queensland.
[src:australian-rules-football/1982-commonwealth-games] There were large marches on 26 September (2,000 people), 20 September (1000), and a sit-in of 104 people on 4 October.
[src:australian-rules-football/1982-commonwealth-games] Also on that day, around 20 spectators held Aboriginal flags in the stadium during the entire program.
[src:australian-rules-football/1982-commonwealth-games] On 7 October, about 500 people attended another protest, and 400 police arrested 260 people, including then Governor-General's daughter, Ann Stephen.
[src:australian-rules-football/1982-commonwealth-games] The protests were all peaceful, but police came out in force and blocked roads, making arrests under Queensland's *Traffic Act*.
[src:australian-rules-football/1982-commonwealth-games] Activists taking part in the protests included Gary Foley and Bob Weatherall (both leaders of the protest); Billy Craigie; Lyall Munro Jnr; Ross Watson; Wayne Wharton; and Selwyn Johnson and his family.
[src:australian-rules-football/1982-commonwealth-games] Selwyn's brother Hedley Johnson was a musician, of the Brisbane group Mop and the Dropouts.
[src:australian-rules-football/1982-commonwealth-games] Their song, "Brisbane Blacks", written by Mop Conlon, became a kind of anthem for the protests.
[src:australian-rules-football/1982-commonwealth-games] The protests, which were followed by large-scale arrests, are a significant event in the history of the Australian Aboriginal rights movement.
[src:australian-rules-football/1982-commonwealth-games] When the Commonwealth Games returned to Australia in 2018 at the Gold Coast, it drew a series of peaceful protests.
[src:australian-rules-football/1982-commonwealth-games] The documentary *Guniwaya Ngigu* also called *We Fight* (1982) follows the Aboriginal protest movement during the Commonwealth Games, and was directed by Madeline McGrady and Tracey Moffatt, and produced by Maureen Watson, Tiga Bayles and Madeline McGrady.
[src:australian-rules-football/1982-commonwealth-games] In 2009 as part of the Q150 celebrations, the 1982 Commonwealth Games were announced as one of the Q150 Icons of Queensland for its role as a "Defining Moment".
[src:australian-rules-football/1982-commonwealth-games] Brisbane also bid for the 1992 Summer Olympics but lost to Barcelona.
[src:australian-rules-football/1982-commonwealth-games] Queensland Premier Annastacia Palaszczuk announced on 9 December 2019 that the state will make an official bid for the 2032 Summer Olympics and Paralympics featuring venues across Brisbane, Gold Coast and Sunshine Coast.
[src:australian-rules-football/1982-commonwealth-games] In 2021, the city won the bid to host the 2032 Summer Olympics and Paralympics.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] During general play, players may position themselves anywhere on the field and use any part of their bodies to move the ball.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] The primary methods are kicking, handballing, and running with the ball.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] There are rules on how the ball can be handled; for example, players running with the ball must intermittently bounce or touch it on the ground.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] Throwing the ball is not allowed, and players must not get caught holding the ball.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] A distinctive feature of the game is the mark, where players anywhere on the field who catch the ball from a kick (with specific conditions) are awarded unimpeded possession.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] Possession of the ball is in dispute at all times except when a free kick or mark is paid.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] Players can tackle using their hands or use their whole body to obstruct opponents.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] Dangerous physical contact (such as pushing an opponent in the back), interference when marking, and deliberately slowing the play are discouraged with free kicks, distance penalties, or suspension for a certain number of matches depending on the severity of the infringement.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] The game features frequent physical contests, spectacular marking, fast movement of both players and the ball, and high scoring.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] The sport's origins can be traced to football matches played in Melbourne, Victoria, in 1858, inspired by English public school football games.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] Seeking to develop a game more suited to adults and Australian conditions, the Melbourne Football Club published the first laws of Australian football in May 1859.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] Australian football has the highest spectator attendance of all sports in Australia while the Australian Football League (AFL), the sport's only fully professional competition, is the nation's wealthiest sporting body.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] The AFL Grand Final, held annually at the 100,000-capacity Melbourne Cricket Ground, is the highest-attended club championship event of any football code.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] The sport is also played at amateur level in many countries and in several variations.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] Its rules are governed by the AFL Commission with the advice of the AFL's Laws of the Game Committee.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] Australian football is known by several nicknames, including Australian rules football, Aussie rules, football and footy.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] In some regions, where other codes of football are more popular, the sport is most often called AFL after the Australian Football League, while the league itself also uses this name for local competitions in some areas.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] Primitive forms of football were played sporadically in the Australian colonies in the first half of the 19th century.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] Compared to cricket and horse racing, football was considered a mere "amusement" by colonists at the time, and while little is known about these early one-off games, evidence does not support a causal link with Australian football.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] In Melbourne, in 1858, in a move that would help to shape Australian football in its formative years, private schools (then termed "public schools" in accordance with nomenclature in England) began organising football games inspired by precedents at English public schools.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] The earliest match, held on 15 June, was between Melbourne Grammar and St Kilda Grammar.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] On 10 July 1858, the Melbourne-based *Bell's Life in Victoria and Sporting Chronicle* published a letter by Tom Wills, captain of the Victoria cricket team, calling for the formation of a "foot-ball club" with a "code of laws" to keep cricketers fit during winter.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] Born in Australia, Wills played a nascent form of rugby football while a pupil at Rugby School in England, and returned to his homeland a star athlete and cricketer.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] Two weeks later, Wills' friend, cricketer Jerry Bryant, posted an advertisement for a scratch match at the Richmond Paddock adjoining the Melbourne Cricket Ground (MCG).
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] This was the first of several "kickabouts" held that year involving members of the Melbourne Cricket Club, including Wills, Bryant, W.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] Trees were used as goalposts and play typically lasted an entire afternoon.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] Without an agreed-upon code of laws, some players were guided by rules they had learned in the British Isles, "others by no rules at all".
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] Another milestone in 1858 was a 40-a-side match played under experimental rules between Melbourne Grammar and Scotch College, held at the Richmond Paddock.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] Umpired by Wills and teacher John Macadam, it began on 7 August and continued over two subsequent Saturdays, ending in a draw with each side kicking one goal.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] It is commemorated with a statue outside the MCG, and the two schools have since competed annually in the Cordner–Eggleston Cup, the world's oldest continuous football competition.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] Since the 1920s, it has been suggested that Australian football may have been derived from the Irish sport of Gaelic football.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] However, there is no archival evidence in favour of a Gaelic influence, and the style of play shared between the two modern codes appeared in Australia long before the Irish game evolved in a similar direction.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] Another theory, first proposed in 1983, posits that Wills, having grown up among Aboriginals in Victoria, may have seen or played the Aboriginal ball game of Marn Grook, and incorporated some of its features into early Australian football.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] There is only circumstantial evidence that he knew of the game, and according to biographer Greg de Moore's research, Wills was "almost solely influenced by his experience at Rugby School".
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] A loosely organised Melbourne side, captained by Wills, played against other football enthusiasts in the winter and spring of 1858.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] The following year, on 14 May, the Melbourne Football Club was officially established, making it one of the world's oldest football clubs.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] Three days later, Wills, Hammersley, Thompson and teacher Thomas H.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] Smith met near the MCG at the Parade Hotel, owned by Bryant, and drafted ten rules: "The Rules of the Melbourne Football Club".
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] These are the laws from which Australian football evolved.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] The club aimed to create a simple code suited to the hard playing surfaces around Melbourne, and to eliminate the roughest aspects of English school games—such as "hacking" (shin-kicking) in Rugby School football—to reduce the risk of injuries to working men.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] In another significant departure from English public school football, the Melbourne rules omitted any offside law.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] "The new code was as much a reaction against the school games as influenced by them", writes Mark Pennings.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] The rules were distributed throughout the colony; Thompson in particular did much to promote the new code in his capacity as a journalist.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] Following Melbourne's lead, Geelong and Melbourne University also formed football clubs in 1859.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] While many early Victorian teams participated in one-off matches, most had not yet formed clubs for regular competition.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] A South Yarra club devised its own rules.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] To ensure the supremacy of the Melbourne rules, the first club-level competition in Australia, the Caledonian Society's Challenge Cup (1861–64), stipulated that only the Melbourne rules were to be used.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] This law was reinforced by the Athletic Sports Committee (ASC), which ran a variation of the Challenge Cup in 1865–66.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] With input from other clubs, the rules underwent several minor revisions, establishing a uniform code known as "Victorian rules".
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] In 1866, the "first distinctively Victorian rule", the running bounce, was formalised at a meeting of club delegates chaired by H.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] Harrison, an influential pioneer who took up football in 1859 at the invitation of Wills, his cousin.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] The game around this time was defensive and low-scoring, played low to the ground in congested rugby-style scrimmages.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] The typical match was a 20-per-side affair, played with a ball that was roughly spherical, and lasted until a team scored two goals.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] The shape of the playing field was not standardised; matches often took place in rough, tree-spotted public parks, most notably the Richmond Paddock (Yarra Park), known colloquially as the Melbourne Football Ground.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] Wills argued that the turf of cricket fields would benefit from being trampled upon by footballers in winter, and, as early as 1859, football was allowed on the MCG.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] However, cricket authorities frequently prohibited football on their grounds until the 1870s, when they saw an opportunity to capitalise on the sport's growing popularity.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] Football gradually adapted to an oval-shaped field, and most grounds in Victoria expanded to accommodate the dual purpose—a situation that continues to this day.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] Football became organised in South Australia in 1860 with the formation of the Adelaide Football Club, the oldest football club in Australia outside Victoria.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] It devised its own rules, and, along with other Adelaide-based clubs, played a variety of codes until 1876, when they uniformly adopted most of the Victorian rules, with South Australian football pioneer Charles Kingston noting their similarity to "the old Adelaide rules".
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] Similarly, Tasmanian clubs quarrelled over different rules until they adopted a slightly modified version of the Victorian game in 1879.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] The South Australian Football Association (SAFA), the sport's first governing body, formed on 30 April 1877, firmly establishing Victorian rules as the preferred code in that colony.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] The Victorian Football Association (VFA) formed the following month.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] Clubs began touring the colonies in the late 1870s, and in 1879 the first intercolonial match took place in Melbourne between Victoria and South Australia.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] In 1883, delegates representing the football associations of South Australia, Tasmania, Victoria and Queensland met to standardise the code across Australia.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] Likewise, when New Zealand experienced a gold rush, the sport arrived with a rapid influx of Australian miners.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] Now known as Australian rules or Australasian rules, the sport became the first football code to develop mass spectator appeal, attracting world record attendances for sports viewing and gaining a reputation as "the people's game".
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] Australian rules football reached Queensland and New South Wales as early as 1866; the sport experienced a period of dominance in the former, and in the latter, several regions remain strongholds of Australian rules, such as the Riverina.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] However, by the late 1880s, rugby football had become the dominant code in both colonies, as well as in New Zealand.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] This shift was largely due to rugby's spread with British migration, regional rivalries and the lack of strong local governing bodies.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] In the case of Sydney, denial of access to grounds, the influence of university headmasters from Britain who favoured rugby, and the loss of players to other codes inhibited the game's growth.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] In 1896, delegates from six of the wealthiest VFA clubs—Carlton, Essendon, Fitzroy, Geelong, Melbourne and South Melbourne—met to discuss the formation of a breakaway professional competition.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] Later joined by Collingwood and St Kilda, the clubs formed the Victorian Football League (VFL), which held its inaugural season in 1897.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] The VFL's popularity grew rapidly as it made several innovations, such as instituting a finals system, reducing teams from 20 to 18 players, and introducing the behind as a score.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] Richmond and University joined the VFL in 1908, and by 1925, with the addition of Hawthorn, Footscray and North Melbourne, it had become the preeminent league in the country and would take a leading role in many aspects of the sport.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] The time around the federation of the Australian colonies in 1901 saw Australian rules undergo a revival in New South Wales, New Zealand and Queensland.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] In 1903, both the Queensland Australian Football League and the NSW Australian Football Association were established, and in New Zealand, as it moved towards becoming a dominion, leagues were also established in the major cities.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] This renewed popularity helped encourage the formation of the Australasian Football Council, which in 1908 in Melbourne staged the first national interstate competition, the Jubilee Australasian Football Carnival, with teams representing each state and New Zealand.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] The game was also established early on in the new territories.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] In the new national capital Canberra both soccer and rugby had a head start, but following the first matches in 1911, Australian rules football in the Australian Capital Territory became a major participation sport.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] By 1981 it had become much neglected and quickly lagged behind the other football codes.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] Australian rules football in the Northern Territory began shortly after the outbreak of the war in 1916 with the first match in Darwin.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] The game went on to become the most popular sport in the Territory and build the highest participation rate for the sport nationally.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] Both World War I and World War II had a devastating effect on Australian football and on Australian sport in general.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] While scratch matches were played by Australian "diggers" in remote locations around the world, the game lost many of its great players to wartime service.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] Some clubs and competitions never fully recovered.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] Between 1914 and 1915, a proposed hybrid code of Australian football and rugby league, the predominant code of football in New South Wales and Queensland, was trialled without success.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] In Queensland, the state league went into recess for the duration of the war.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] VFL club University left the league and went into recess due to severe casualties.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] The West Australian Football League (WAFL) lost two clubs and the SANFL was suspended for one year in 1916 due to heavy club losses.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] The Anzac Day match, the annual game between Essendon and Collingwood on Anzac Day, is one example of how the war continues to be remembered in the football community.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] The role of the Australian National Football Council (ANFC) was primarily to govern the game at a national level and to facilitate interstate representative and club competition.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] In 1968, the ANFC revived the Championship of Australia, a competition first held in 1888 between the premiers of the VFA and SAFA.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] Although clubs from other states were at times invited, the final was almost always between the premiers from the two strongest state competitions of the time—South Australia and Victoria—with Adelaide hosting most of the matches at the request of the SAFA/SANFL.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] The last match took place in 1976, with North Adelaide being the last non-Victorian winner in 1972.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] Between 1976 and 1987, the ANFC, and later the Australian Football Championships (AFC) ran a night series, which invited clubs and representative sides from around the country to participate in a knock-out tournament parallel to the premiership seasons, which Victorian sides still dominated.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] With the lack of international competition, state representative matches were regarded with great importance.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] Due in part to the VFL poaching talent from other states, Victoria dominated interstate matches for three-quarters of a century.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] State of Origin rules, introduced in 1977, stipulated that rather than representing the state of their adopted club, players would return to play for the state they were first recruited in.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] This instantly broke Victoria's stranglehold over state titles and Western Australia and South Australia began to win more of their games against Victoria.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] Both New South Wales and Tasmania scored surprise victories at home against Victoria in 1990.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] The term "Barassi Line", named after VFL star Ron Barassi, was coined by scholar Ian Turner in 1978 to describe the "fictitious geographical barrier" separating the rugby-following parts of New South Wales and Queensland from the rest of the country, where Australian football reigned.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] It became a reference point for the expansion of Australian football and for establishing a national league.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] The way the game was played had changed dramatically due to innovative coaching tactics, with the phasing out of many of the game's kicking styles and the increasing use of handball; while presentation was influenced by television.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] In 1982, in a move that heralded big changes within the sport, one of the original VFL clubs, South Melbourne, relocated to Sydney and became known as the Sydney Swans.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] In the late 1980s, due to the poor financial standing of many of the Victorian clubs, and a similar situation existing in Western Australia in the sport, the VFL pursued a more national competition.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] Two more non-Victorian clubs, West Coast and Brisbane, joined the league in 1987 generating more than $8 million in license revenue for the Victorian clubs and increasing broadcast revenues which helped the Victorian clubs survive.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] In their early years, the Sydney and Brisbane clubs struggled both on and off-field because the substantial TV revenues they generated by playing on a Sunday went to the VFL.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] To protect these revenues the VFL granted significant draft concessions and financial aid to keep the expansion clubs competitive.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] The VFL changed its name to the Australian Football League (AFL) for the 1990 season, and over the next decade, three non-Victorian clubs gained entry: Adelaide (1991), Fremantle (1995) and the SANFL's Port Adelaide (1997), the only pre-existing club outside Victoria to join the league.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] In 2011 and 2012, respectively, two new non-Victorian clubs were added to the competition: Gold Coast and Greater Western Sydney.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] The AFL, currently with 18 member clubs, is the sport's elite competition and most powerful body.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] Following the emergence of the AFL, state leagues were quickly relegated to a second-tier status.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] The VFA merged with the former VFL reserves competition in 1998, adopting the VFL name.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] State of Origin also declined in importance, especially after an increasing number of player withdrawals.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] The AFL turned its focus to the annual International Rules Series against Ireland in 1998 before abolishing State of Origin the following year.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] State and territorial leagues still contest interstate matches, as do AFL Women players.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] In the 2010s, the AFL signalled further attempts at expanding into markets outside Australian football's traditional heartlands by hosting home-and-away matches in New Zealand, followed by China.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] After several failed bids since the early 1990s for a Tasmania-based AFL team, the Tasmania Football Club secured the 19th AFL license in 2023, and is set to compete by 2028.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] In a standard match, a team may consist of anywhere between 14 and 18 players who may be permitted on the playing surface at any given time.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] Each team may have up to four interchange (reserve) players who may be swapped for those on the field at any time during the game, although some leagues in less populated areas may use as few as 12 players.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] In addition, some leagues, notably including the AFL, have each team designate one additional player as a substitute who can be used to make a single permanent exchange of players during a game for either medical or tactical reasons.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] Players on the playing surface can be swapped with those on the interchange bench at any time.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] They must though pass through a designated "Interchange Area".
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] In the event a player fails to pass through this area correctly, or if too many players from one team are found to be on the ground at a time, a free kick will be awarded to the opposing side.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] Players may wear certain pieces of protective equipment, such as helmets or arm guards, if approved by the relevant controlling body.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] Mouthguards are strongly recommended for all players.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] Players are not permitted to wear jewellery, or other materials which the field umpire has deemed to be either potentially dangerous or increase the risk of injury to other players.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] Australian rules football is played with an ellipsoid ball, between 72 and 73 cm (28 and 29 in) in long circumference, and 54.5 and 55.5 cm (21.5 and 21.9 in) in short circumference.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] For women's competitions, a smaller ball size of 69 and 53 cm (27 and 21 in) is used.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] The ball must be inflated to a pressure of 69 kilopascals (10.0 pounds per square inch).
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] There are no defined laws regarding what material a ball must be made from, but standard AFL match-used balls are produced by Sherrin using cowhide leather.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] While there is no standard colour of the ball, red and yellow are most common and the only colours used at AFL level.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] Yellow is used for games beginning after 3 pm or in an enclosed stadium, due to its greater visibility, and to assist score reviews.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] Unlike other forms of football which are played on rectangular fields, Australian rules football playing fields are oval-shaped, and are between 135 and 185 metres (148 and 202 yd) long and 110 and 155 metres (120 and 170 yd) wide.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] At either end of the field, two sets of posts are erected in a straight line to indicate the scoring areas on the field, each with two kinds of posts, named the goal posts and the behind posts respectively.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] The goal posts are placed first, located 6.4 metres (7.0 yd) apart from each other, with a behind post being placed a further 6.4 metres to the side of each goal post.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] The name for the field line between two goal posts is known as the Goal Line.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] Around the perimeter of the field, two white lines are drawn between the set of behind posts in an arc-shape, marking the field of play.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] The 50m arcs, centre square, centre circle and goal square are used at the beginning of each quarter or after each goal.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] Each team is permitted a maximum of six players in each 50m arc, with one in the goal square and four players in the centre square with one in the centre circle.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] If this is breached, a free kick is awarded.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] A game lasts for 80 minutes, split into four quarters consisting of 20 minutes playing time, with the clock being stopped for stoppages in play such as scores, or at the umpire's discretion, e.g. for serious injury.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] Leagues may choose to employ shorter quarters of play at their discretion, such as the AFLW using 17 minutes per quarter.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] For any given match, two timekeepers are appointed to officiate the duration.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] The timekeepers record all relevant statistics for the match, such as total quarter duration and score by each team.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] Additionally timekeepers are required to sound a siren prior to and at the conclusion of each quarter until such time they are acknowledged by the field umpires.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] To stop and recommence the clock, the field umpires are required to signal to the timekeepers to indicate when the clock should be stopped or restarted.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] Between each quarter, a break is observed to allow players a rest period.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] Two six-minute breaks are observed between the first and second quarters, and the third and fourth quarters.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] A longer 20-minute break is observed between the second and third quarter, commonly known as *half-time*.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] Each game is officiated by at least five match officials, known as an umpire.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] At AFL level, a video score review system is utilised.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] Only umpires are permitted to request a review, and only scoring shots and potential scoring shots are permitted to be reviewed.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] An Australian rules football may only be propelled forward in a select few ways as defined by the Laws of Australian Football, published by the AFL.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] The ball can be propelled in any direction by way of a kick or a clenched fist (called a handball)—deemed a correct disposal.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] Failure to dispose of the ball in one of these two methods will result in a free kick to the opposing team.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] If the ball is not currently in a player's possession, it can be moved legally through the usage of other means, such as punching.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] While in possession of the ball, players may run with the ball, but are required to either bounce or touch the ball on the ground at least once every 15 metres (16 yd).
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] Tackling is a technique employed by players used to force opposition players to dispose of the ball when they are in possession.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] Failure to dispose of the ball when legally tackled may see the player penalised for 'holding the ball', except if the umpire deems there was a lack of prior opportunity to do so.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] The ball carrier may only be tackled between the shoulders and knees from the front or side.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] If the player forcefully contacts the opposing in the back while performing a tackle, the opposition player will be penalised for a push in the back.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] If the opposition tackles the player with possession below the knees (a *low tackle* or a *trip*) or above the shoulders (a *high tackle*), the team with possession of the football gets a free kick.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] Furthermore, tackles deemed to be dangerous by the umpire and those conducted from front-on while an opposition player has their head over the football are deemed to be prohibited contact, and will incur a free kick against the offending player.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] Additionally, players may perform a technique known shepherding when the ball is within 5 metres (5.5 yd) of an opposition player.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] Shepherding involves the use of a player's body to push, bump or otherwise block an opposition player, providing they do not have possession of the ball.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] If a player takes possession of the ball that has travelled more than 15 metres (16 yd) from another player's kick, by way of a catch within the field of play, it is deemed as a *mark*.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] To be awarded a mark, it must be deemed that the player sufficiently controlled the ball and took possession prior to it being touched, touching the ground, or in the case of a contest, being spoiled by an opponent.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] Upon a mark being taken, one opposition player may choose to stand on the point on the field where the mark was taken, known as "the mark".
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] When a mark is taken, a small protected zone is established on the field, extending 10 metres (11 yd) either side of "the mark" and the player who marked the ball, with a small protected corridor between "the mark" and the player.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] The opposition player is permitted to jump, but is not allowed to move from their position on "the mark".
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] Any other movements result in a distance penalty (50 metres in the AFL).
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] The player who was awarded the mark may then choose to either dispose of the ball over "the mark" or may choose to attempt disposal via a different method, in which case the field umpire will call "play on"—a verbal instruction to continue play.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] "Play on" may also be called if the umpire deems the player awarded the mark to be taking an unreasonable amount of time to dispose of the football.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] Once the player has disposed of the ball, or "play on" is called, normal play resumes.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] Rucking is the only specialist skill and is performed by a ruck, the term for designated players from each side to which the umpire sends the ball to commence play.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] Only a nominated ruck may contest ball-ups and throw-ins.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] They are the only player allowed within the 10 metre circle at a centre bounce.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] Functionally the role is analogous to a basketball centre and as such rucks are typically the tallest player on the team.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] Lifting teammates is not allowed so the ruck may only jump to reach the ball.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] If the ruck does not take possession of the football, it must be tapped or fisted, which is known as a hit-out.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] An effective hit-out that passes the ball to a teammate is known as a hit-out to advantage.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] In the event a player breaks a rule, a free kick is awarded to the opposing team, from the location that the misconduct occurred, or the ball's current location—whichever is closer to the team's scoring zone.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] As when a mark is taken, this location is called "the mark", and the same protections regarding the space apply.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] In the event a player engages in unsportsmanlike conduct after a free kick has been awarded or a mark has been paid to the opposing team, the umpire may instead award a 50-metre penalty.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] When imposed, the field umpire will advance "the mark" an additional 50 metres (55 yd) down the field or to the goal line, whichever is closer.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] Additional 50-metre penalties may be awarded if the behaviour continues after the initial penalty.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] The laws of the game allow umpires to send off players for egregious foul play, although this law does not apply to the AFL and is largely only used at the local level.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] There are two types of scoring shots in Australian football: goals and behinds.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] A *goal* is worth six points, and is scored when the football is propelled between the goal posts and across the goal line at any height by way of a kick from the attacking team.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] It may touch the ground, but must not have been touched by any player from either team or a goalpost prior to crossing the goal line.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] A behind is also awarded to the team if the ball touches any part of an opposition player, including a foot, before passing across their goal or behind line.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] A free kick is awarded against any player who is deemed to have deliberately rushed a behind.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] The team that has scored the most points at the end of play wins the game.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] If the scores are level on points at the end of play, then the game is a draw; extra time applies only during finals matches in some competitions.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] As an example of a score report, consider a match between Sydney and Geelong with the former as the home team.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] Sydney's score of 17 goals and 5 behinds equates to 107 points.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] Geelong's score of 10 goals and 17 behinds equates to a 77-point tally.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] Sydney wins the match by a margin of 30 points.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] "Sydney, seventeen-five, one hundred and seven, defeated Geelong, ten-seventeen, seventy-seven".
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] The home team is typically listed first and the visiting side is listed second.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] The football season proper is from March to August (early autumn to late winter in Australia), with finals being held in September and October.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] In the tropics, the game is sometimes played in the wet season (October to March).
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] The AFL is recognised by the Australian Sports Commission as being the National Sporting Organisation for Australian rules.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] There are also seven state/territory-based organisations in Australia, all of which are affiliated with the AFL.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] These state leagues hold annual semi-professional club competitions, with some also overseeing more than one league.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] Local semi-professional or amateur organisations and competitions are often affiliated to their state organisations.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] In 2003, the AFL became the *de facto* world governing body for Australian football when it pushed for the closure of the International Australian Football Council.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] There are also a number of affiliated organisations governing amateur clubs and competitions around the world.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] In Australian football club competitions, the aim is to win the premiership (also known as the "flag"), which is typically decided by a finals series.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] The teams that occupy the highest positions on the ladder after the home-and-away season play-off in a "semi-knockout" finals series, culminating in a single Grand Final match to determine the premiers.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] Between four and eight teams contest a finals series, typically using the AFL final eight system or a variation of the McIntyre system.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] The team which finishes first on the ladder after the home-and-away season is referred to as the "minor premier", but this usually holds little stand-alone significance, other than receiving a better draw in the finals.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] Some metropolitan leagues have several tiered divisions, with promotion of the lower division premiers and relegation of the upper division's last placed team at the end of each year.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] The high level of interest shown by women in Australian football is considered unique among the world's football codes.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] It was the case in the 19th century, as it is in modern times, that women made up approximately half of total attendances at Australian football matches—a far greater proportion than, for example, the estimated 10 per cent of women that comprise British soccer crowds.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] This has been attributed in part to the egalitarian character of Australian football's early years in public parks where women could mingle freely and support the game in various ways.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] In terms of participation, there are occasional 19th-century references to women playing the sport, but it was not until the 1910s that the first organised women's teams and competitions appeared.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] Women's state leagues emerged in the 1980s, and in 2013, the AFL announced plans to establish a national semi-professional women's competition.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] Amidst a surge in viewing interest and participation in women's football, the AFL pushed the founding date of the competition, named AFL Women's (AFLW), to 2017.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] Eight AFL clubs won licences to field sides in its inaugural season.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] By 2022, all 18 clubs fielded an AFLW side, and there will be 19 teams with the admission of Tasmania to the competition in 2028.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] Many related games have emerged from Australian football, mainly with variations of contact to encourage greater participation.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] These include Auskick (played by children aged between 5 and 12), kick-to-kick (and its variants end-to-end footy and marks up), rec footy, 9-a-side footy, masters Australian football, handball and longest-kick competitions.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] Players outside Australia sometimes engage in related games adapted to available fields, like metro footy (played on gridiron fields) and Samoa rules (played on rugby fields).
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] One such prominent example in use since 2018 is AFLX, a shortened variation of the game with seven players a side, played on a soccer-sized pitch.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] The similarities between Australian football and the Irish sport of Gaelic football have allowed for the creation of a hybrid code known as international rules football.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] The first international rules matches were contested in Ireland during the 1967 Australian Football World Tour.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] Since then, various sets of compromise rules have been trialed, and in 1984 the International Rules Series commenced with national representative sides selected by Australia's state leagues (later by the AFL) and the Gaelic Athletic Association (GAA).
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] The competition became an annual event in 1998, but was postponed indefinitely in 2007 when the GAA pulled out due to Australia's severe and aggressive style of play.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] It resumed in Australia in 2008 under new rules to protect the player with the ball.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] During the colonial period, Australian rules was sometimes referred to as Australasian rules, reflecting its popularity in New Zealand.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] The game was played outside Australasia as early as 1888 when Australians studying at Edinburgh University and London University formed teams and competed in London.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] Further international exposure came that same year, when the first British rugby side to tour the Southern Hemisphere played Australian rules matches in both Australia and New Zealand.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] By the early 20th century, it had spread with the Australian diaspora to South Africa, the United States and other parts of the Anglosphere; however this growth went into rapid decline during and after World War I, leading also to a decades long hiatus in New Zealand.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] After World War II, it experienced growth in the Pacific region, particularly in Papua New Guinea and Nauru, where it is now the national sport.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] Today, the sport is played at an amateur level in various countries throughout the world.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] Twenty-three countries have participated in the International Cup, which was held triennially in Australia from 2002 to 2017.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] International competition resumed in 2024 with three regional tournaments: the Transatlantic Cup, Asia Cup, and Pacific Cup.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] Nine countries have also participated in the AFL Europe Championship.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] In 2013, participation across AFL Europe's 21 member nations was more than 5,000 players, the majority of which are European nationals rather than Australian expats.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] The sport also has a growing presence in India.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] Over 20 countries have either affiliation or working agreements with the AFL.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] Most present-day international amateur clubs and leagues are based in North America, Europe and Asia, with the oldest typically having originated in the 1980s.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] That decade, the sport developed a cult following in the United States when matches were broadcast on the fledgling ESPN network.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] Growing international interest has been assisted by exhibition matches, players switching between football codes, and Australia's multicultural makeup.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] Many VFL/AFL players were born overseas, with a growing number recruited through various initiatives.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] One notable example is the Irish experiment, which, since the 1980s, has seen many Gaelic footballers leave the amateur GAA to play Australian rules professionally.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] This has expanded to women's football, with 39 Irish players on AFLW lists for the 2025 season.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] Although Australian rules football is not an Olympic sport, it was showcased at the MCG as part of the 1956 Summer Olympics, held in Melbourne.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] In addition, when Brisbane hosted the 1982 Commonwealth Games, an exhibition match between Richmond and Carlton was held at the Gabba.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] Australian football has attracted more overall interest among Australians than any other football code.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] The 2024 AFL season saw an average attendance of 38,344 fans per match, making the AFL Australia's, and one of the world's best-attended sports leagues.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] Also that year, data indicated 1,319,687 people, or 1 in 20 Australians, are members of an AFL club.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] The most-visited sports website in Australia in 2023 was the AFL's, attracting 1.89 billion total visits.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] Approximately 40% of Australians aged 14+ watch AFL matches on TV either occasionally or regularly.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] The 2024 AFL Grand Final was that year's highest-rating free-to-air television broadcast in Australia, with an in-home audience of 4 million watching Seven's coverage; overall TV viewership reached at least 7,569,000.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] The AFL's current TV broadcasting rights deal with Seven and Foxtel is worth an Australian record $4.5 billion.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] In terms of participation, there were at least 581,000 registered players in Australia in 2024.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] This figure encompasses community football at junior, youth, and senior levels, as well as programs such as Footy 9s.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] Among Australian children aged 0–14, it is the fifth most common sporting activity, behind swimming, soccer, basketball and gymnastics.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] Women and girls account for 20% of all community football registrations.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] Australian football has inspired works by many writers and poets, including C.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] Dennis, Helen Garner, Peter Goldsworthy and Kerry Greenwood.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] Historians Manning Clarke and Geoffrey Blainey have also written extensively on the sport.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] Slang within Australian football has impacted Australian English more broadly, with a number of expressions taking on new meanings in non-sporting contexts, e.g., to "get a guernsey" is to gain recognition or approval, while "shirt-fronting" someone is to accost them.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] In 1889, Australian impressionist painter Arthur Streeton captured football games *en plein air* for the 9 by 5 Impression Exhibition, titling one work *The National Game*.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] Paintings by Sidney Nolan (*Footballer*, 1946) and John Brack (*Three of the Players*, 1953) helped to establish Australian football as a serious subject for modernists, and many Aboriginal artists have explored the game, often fusing it with the mythology of their region.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] Vincent Namatjira won the 2020 Archibald Prize for his portrait of Adam Goodes.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] In cartooning, WEG's VFL/AFL premiership posters—inaugurated in 1954—have achieved iconic status among Australian football fans.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] Australian football statues can be found throughout the country, some based on famous photographs, among them Haydn Bunton Sr.'s leap, Jack Dyer's charge and Nicky Winmar lifting his jumper.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] In the 1980s, a group of postmodern architects based in Melbourne began incorporating references to Australian football into their buildings, an example being Building 8 by Edmond and Corrigan.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] Dance sequences based on Australian football feature heavily in Robert Helpmann's 1964 ballet *The Display*, his first and most famous work for the Australian Ballet.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] The game has also inspired well-known plays such as *And the Big Men Fly* (1963) by Alan Hopgood and David Williamson's *The Club* (1977), which was adapted into a 1980 film, directed by Bruce Beresford.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] Mike Brady's 1979 hit "Up There Cazaly" is considered an Australian football anthem, and references to the sport can be found in works by popular musicians, from singer-songwriter Paul Kelly to the alternative rock band TISM.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] Others, such as Tame Impala's Kevin Parker, have written songs for their favourite AFL club.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] Many Australian football video games have been released, notably the AFL series.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] For the centenary of the VFL/AFL in 1996, the Australian Football Hall of Fame was established.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] That year, 136 significant figures across the various competitions were inducted into the Hall of Fame.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] Each years since the creation of the Hall of Fame, a panel selects a small group of players they deem worthy for this prestigious honour, resulting in a total number of more than 300 inductees as of 2024.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] In addition to the Hall of Fame, select members are chosen to receive the elite *Legend* status.
[src:australian-rules-football/australian-rules-football] Due to restrictions limiting the number of Legend status players to 10% of the total number of Hall of Fame inductees, there are currently only 32 players with the status in the Hall of Fame as of 2024.
